â€œTheyâ€™ve been busting out solid Celtic punk rock for over a decade, yet youâ€™ll still find kids on the internet calling them out for ripping off bands like Dropkick Murphys and Flogging Molly, both of whom came out of the gates a few years after the McKenzies released their first album in 1996 and were doubtlessly influenced by the bandâ€™s sound and look.â€ â€“ Exclaim MagazineYou know these songs. Thatâ€™s because the twelve anthemsâ€”and make no mistake, these are anthemsâ€”The Real McKenzies have picked for this new album have been sung by others for decades, if not centuries. A dual celebration of Scottishness and the band, which is celebrating its 30th anniversary this year, Songs Of The Highland, Songs Of The Sea drops on Fat Wreck Chords on November 18th and is comprised entirely of famous traditional sea shanties that are roughly divided, as the recordâ€™s title suggest, between land and sea. And even though the idea for the album was initially proposed by guitarist Mario Nieva, these songs speak to frontman Paul McKenzieâ€™s heritage as well as who he is, and who he always has been. Some might have been written long before he was born, but these are still his stories, wound inextricably into his life experiences. â€œMario thought we should attempt to do this,â€ he explains. â€œIt wouldnâ€™t take a lot of time in terms of writing, because all the songs were already written. In fact, most of the songs are ancient. Theyâ€™re really old. I myself, being completely nautical, unfortunately due to the pandemic, had to sell my ship, because I just simply couldnâ€™t afford it, much like Angus Walters, who sold The Bluenose. That ship is on the Canadian 10 cent piece, so every Canadian can have reference to that piece of history, although a lot of Canadians now donâ€™t give a shit now, or donâ€™t know.â€ To some extent, these songs are their own references to that history, brought up to date by the Vancouver, BC-based band and given a Celtic punk makeover. How else could it start, then, than with the â€œScotland The Braveâ€? But here, its recognizable bagpipe melody soon gives way toâ€” and then joined in unison byâ€”electric guitars in a perfect confluence of past and present. Thatâ€™s the pattern throughout this record. Old songs are imbued with new relevance for these modern times, and delivered with the kind of intensity and passion that only someone in tune with the history of the music and the country could deliver so emphatically. As the only constant and remaining member in the bandâ€™s history, he does so with a relatively new collection of merry music makers, but it sounds like theyâ€™ve been playing together for years and years. â€œYou can really hear the camaraderie on these songs,â€ says McKenzie. â€œThere was never any contention when we were making it, but if there was a question, weâ€™d sit down just like the sailors did and talk about it. Because the last thing you need when youâ€™re in a vanâ€”or a sailing shipâ€”is contention. Because the next step is keelhauling...â€ If youâ€™re unaware, keelhauling is an old-fashioned method of extreme torture and execution, where a sailor would be thrown overboard on one side of the ship and then dragged its keel. McKenzie is joking, of course, but having suffered something of a mutiny just before the pandemic, when his entire band at the time decided to call it quits, it certainly explains just how heâ€™s able to infuse these ancient marinersâ€™ rhymes with such emotion and depth of feeling. Thatâ€™s especially impressive considering a number of these songsâ€™ lyricsâ€”â€œMy Heartâ€™s In The Highlandsâ€, â€œYe Jacobites By Nameâ€ and â€œA Red, Red Roseâ€â€”were written by the 18th century Scottish poet Robert Burns. That might seem like an odd thing for a punk band to do, but anyone who knows The Real McKenzies will be aware itâ€™s not the first time theyâ€™ve sung his words. Indeed, the singer has a real soft spot for the literary legend. â€œNobody else in the world is doing Robert Burns in that format,â€ he says. â€œI was raised with Robert Burns and I just love him. I think weâ€™ve covered 15 of his songs. One of the things about Canada that you have to understand is that in the â€™20s, Robert Burns was fucking huge, and Scottish music was also huge there back then. Even today, thereâ€™s a Robert Burns statue in every major city in Canada.â€ This album is only partially Robert Burns, though. It also includes wonderfully life-affirming (yet somehow still melancholy) versions of two of the best known sea shanties, â€œDrunken Sailorâ€ and â€œDead Manâ€™s Chestâ€, though the latter was a actually fictional one created by Robert Louis Stevenson for his iconic 1883 novel Treasure Island). Thereâ€™s also a gorgeously resigned rendition of â€œSloop John Bâ€, the Bahamian sea shanty popularized by The Beach Boys back in 1966. â€œThey made a Californian pretty boy version of it,â€ says McKenzie, â€œbut itâ€™s not supposed to be that way. Itâ€™s supposed to be a fucking hard ass sailor singing it.â€ And then thereâ€™s the version here of the early 20th century folk song, â€œSwansea Townâ€, a song that means so much to McKenzie he couldnâ€™t even bring himself to sing it. Instead, he got The Last Gang vocalist Brenna Red to fill in. Like all of these songs, itâ€™s one that helped shape him, and which still sits at the very core of who he is all these years later. â€œAt that point in time,â€ he explains, â€œI just couldnâ€™t do it. I was at an emotional stress point at that time in my life. I am a sailor, and Iâ€™ve been sailing since 1963, when I had my first sailing adventure with my grandfather. He was way more of an asshole fucking c*nt than I am. He was renowned for this. My parents used to say â€˜If you misbehave youâ€™ll have to go spend the summer with your grandfather!â€™ They used it as a point of contention and as a threat for me. But unbeknownst to them, my grandfather and I got along great. He taught me everything I know about boats and sailing. Itâ€™s because of him that Iâ€™ve been a sailor my whole life, so when Mario suggested we do this I had to say yes. I have a feeling for all these songs. They mean so much to me.â€ That much is obvious when you listen to this record. Youâ€™ll be singing centuries old songs as if theyâ€™re the pop hits of today. And why shouldnâ€™t they be?
